<div>
  <p>
    This demo uses
    <code>fetchpriority</code>
    to hint the browser to boost the priority of the poster image on the
    <code>&lt;video&gt;</code>
    element.
  </p>
  <video
    poster="./poster.jpg?v=1671553386107"
    controls
    width="1920"
    height="1080"
  >
    <source
      type="video/webm"
      src="./video-1920.webm?v=1671553389855"
    />
    <source
      type="video/mp4"
      src="./video-1920.mp4?v=1671553389855"
    />
  </video>
  <p>
    The below chart compares the performance before and after the
    <code>preload</code>
    hint with
    <code>fetchpriority=&quot;high&quot;</code>
    was added.
  </p>
  <p>
    <img
      src="./after.png?v=1671622156330"
      alt="Waterfall chart showing four resources. The `poster.jpg` image starts downloading in parallel as the other resources and finishes between 1.2 and 1.3 seconds."
      width="1012"
      height="312"
    />
  </p>
  <p>
    In the waterfall above—which includes the
    <code>fetchpriority</code>
    hint—the
    <code>poster.jpg</code>
    image starts downloading in parallel with the other high priority resources
    and finishes at 1.2 seconds.
  </p>
  <p>
    <img
      src="./before.png?v=1671622156330"
      alt="Waterfall chart showing four resources. The `poster.jpg` image starts downloading once `style.css` has finished downloading and finishes between 1.6 and 1.7 seconds."
      width="1012"
      height="312"
    />
  </p>
  <p>
    In the waterfall above, the
    <code>poster.jpg</code>
    image starts downloading once
    <code>style.css</code>
    has finished downloading and finishes at 1.7s. This
    gives us a slower LCP at 1.7s.
  </p>
